{% include imported_disclaimer.html %}
<p>In order to improve the quality of the code produced by you and your team, there are some tools that can help to enforce standards, conventions and code style.</p>
<p><a title="JSHint" href="http://jshint.com/" target="_blank">JSHint</a> is a tool that allows to detect potential errors and to define code standards and conventions. This tool cal help a team to define the standards that everyone should follow when they are writing JavaScript code.</p>
<p>On the other hand, <a title="JSCS" href="http://jscs.info/" target="_blank">JSCS</a> allows to define conventions about code style. For instance, you can define that a space is required after the 'if' keyword, or also that a semicolon is required after statement.</p>
<p>In <a title="Visual Studio Code" href="https://code.visualstudio.com/" target="_blank">Visual Studio Code</a> those tools are not enable by default like in other code editors. However, you can add them manually following the next steps.</p>
<ol>
<li>Download and install the latest version of <a title="Node.js" href="https://nodejs.org/en/" target="_blank">Node.js</a></li>
<li>Check the installed version of Node.js using
<pre class="brush:ps;auto-links:false;toolbar:false" contenteditable="false">node -v</pre>
<img src="data:image/png;base64," alt="" /></li>
<li>Use <a title="npm" href="https://www.npmjs.com/" target="_blank">npm</a>&nbsp;(installed with Node.js) to install JSHint&nbsp;(option -<em>g</em> is to install it globally so you don't need to do it in every project)
<pre class="brush:ps;auto-links:false;toolbar:false" contenteditable="false">npm install -g jshint</pre>
</li>
<li>Use npm to install&nbsp;JSCS
<pre class="brush:ps;auto-links:false;toolbar:false" contenteditable="false">npm install -g jscs</pre>
</li>
<li>Open Visual Studio Code and press <em>F1</em></li>
<li>Enter the following command to install JSHint
<pre class="brush:plain;auto-links:false;toolbar:false" contenteditable="false">ext install (enter) 
jshint</pre>
<img src="/image.axd?picture=/Posts/Installing-JSHint-and-JSCS-in-VSC/2.gif" alt="" /></li>
<li>Enter the following command to install JSCS <br />
<pre class="brush:plain;auto-links:false;toolbar:false" contenteditable="false">ext install (enter) 
jscs</pre>
<img src="data:image/png;base64," alt="" /></li>
<li>JSHint and JSCS are installed</li>
</ol>
<p>Once, you have installed these&nbsp;extensions, you will see some alerts if the code does not&nbsp;meet&nbsp;the default rules.</p>
<p>In the following screens you can see the alerts from&nbsp;JSCS and JSHint.</p>
<p><img style="display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;" src="data:image/png;base64," alt="" /></p>
<p><img style="display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;" src="data:image/png;base64," alt="" /></p>
<p>These alerts are not only to show the code has something wrong but also that can be integrated with an automated task (using <a title="Gulp" href="http://gulpjs.com/" target="_blank">Gulp</a> for example) that is added in your workflow prior to release the code to quality assurance and production environments. But that is a different topic that I would&nbsp;show&nbsp;in another post.</p>
<p>That's it for today.</p>
<p>See you soon in the digital neighborhood!</p>
